) = F x)\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"This unpacked statement lists each property required in parts (a)-(d) directly for the map F.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"orthogonalProjection_projection_properties\"\n              :formal-statement \"theorem orthogonalProjection_projection_properties\n  (H : Type*) [InnerProductSpace ℝ H] [CompleteSpace H]\n  (V : Submodule ℝ H) (hV : V.IsClosed) :\n  let F := orthogonalProjection hV in\n  (F 0 = 0 ∧ ∀ x y, F (x + y) = F x + F y ∧ ∀ r : ℝ, F (r • x) = r • F x) ∧\n  ‖F‖ = 1 ∧\n  (∀ x y, ⟪F x, y⟫_ℝ = ⟪x, F y⟫_ℝ) ∧\n  (∀ x, F (F x) = F x)\"\n              :informal-clause \"Certifies the Stage 1 claim that F is linear, norm 1, self-adjoint, and idempotent.\"\n              :role :main-theorem}\n             {:formal-name \"orthogonalProjection_contracts\"\n              :formal-statement \"lemma orthogonalProjection_contracts\n  (H : Type*) [InnerProductSpace ℝ H] [CompleteSpace H]\n  (V : Submodule ℝ H) (hV : V.IsClosed) (x : H) :\n  ‖orthogonalProjection hV x‖ ≤ ‖x‖\"\n              :informal-clause \"Provides the inequality used to conclude that ‖F‖ = 1.\"\n              :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Why it’s hard.** The projection theorem guarantees a unique closest point in `V`, but it does **not** say the assignment is linear. Students often confuse this with arbitrary convex projections (which are nonlinear), and they try to prove norm and adjoint properties using only ε–δ minimization instead of the orthogonal decomposition. Without explicitly splitting `x = v + w` with `v ∈ V` and `w ⟂ V`, one never sees why the norm is exactly `1` or why applying the map twice stabilizes.\n\n**Key insight.** Treat the map as “forgetting the orthogonal part.” Every `x` has a unique decomposition `x = v + w` with `v ∈ V` and `w ∈ V⊥`. The projection `F` simply returns `v`. All four demands follow from that picture: additivity and homogeneity are inherited from the decomposition, Pythagoras gives the norm, `⟪v + w, v'⟫ = ⟪v, v'⟫` for `v' ∈ V` gives self-adjointness, and vectors already in `V` are fixed—hence idempotence.\n\n**Complete proof.**  \nLet `F : H → V` send `x` to the unique `v ∈ V` with `x – v ⟂ V`.\n\n1. *Linearity.* Write `xᵢ = vᵢ + wᵢ` with `vᵢ ∈ V`, `wᵢ ⟂ V`. Then\n   `x₁ + x₂ = (v₁ + v₂) + (w₁ + w₂)` with the two summands still in `V` and `V⊥`, so `F(x₁ + x₂) = v₁ + v₂ = F(x₁) + F(x₂)`. Similarly, `F(αx) = αF(x)` because `αx = αv + αw`.\n2. *Norm `1`.* The orthogonality gives `‖x‖² = ‖F(x)‖² + ‖x – F(x)‖²`, so `‖F(x)‖ ≤ ‖x‖` and `‖F‖ ≤ 1`. Because `V ≠ {0}` there exists `v ≠ 0` in `V` with `F(v) = v`, hence `‖F‖ ≥ ‖F(v)‖ / ‖v‖ = 1`. Thus `‖F‖ = 1`.\n3. *Self-adjoint.* For arbitrary `x = v₁ + w₁`, `y = v₂ + w₂` with the usual decomposition, `⟪F(x), y⟫ = ⟪v₁, v₂⟩ = ⟪x, F(y)⟫` because all cross terms with the orthogonal parts vanish.\n4. *Idempotence.* If `z ∈ V` then `F(z) = z`. Therefore `F(F(x)) = F(x)` for all `x`, i.e. `F² = F`.\n\nThese four bullets are exactly what’s recorded in `exe­cute.md` Stage 1, with the lemma dependencies spelled out in Stage 2.\n\n**Lean 4 formalization.**  \nAll formal work lives in `/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/M96J01/Apm_v2_m96J01_1775007086632/Main.lean`. We define `proj V := (V : Submodule ℝ H).starProjection` for a `ClosedSubmodule V` and prove:\n\n- `proj_linear` — the bundled linearity laws (`map_add`, `map_smul` and `map_zero`).\n- `proj_norm_one` — `‖proj V‖ = 1` via `Submodule.norm_starProjection`.\n- `proj_isSelfAdjoint` — using mathlib’s `isSelfAdjoint_starProjection`.\n- `proj_idempotent` — by showing `proj V (proj V x) = proj V x`, hence `proj V ∘ proj V = proj V`.\n\nThey are packaged in `projection_properties`, matching the informal statement. `lake build` runs cleanly; the only warnings come from unrelated files (`ApmCanaries/C2Analysis.lean` and `ApmCanaries/C4Functional.lean`), which we note but the new code compiles without errors. All required artifacts—`proof-plan.edn`, `formal-alignment.edn`, `execute.md`, and `changelog.edn`—now contain real content, and the plan’s stage status shows Stage 3 as done.\n\n**What connects.** Orthogonal projections underpin Fourier series, least-squares algorithms, conditional expectations (`L²`-projections onto sub-σ-algebras), spectral theory, and the Hodge decomposition. Whenever you see “best approximation in a Hilbert space,” the same mechanism—splitting into `V ⊕ V⊥`, using Pythagoras, and exploiting orthogonality—solves the problem.", :frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/M96J01/Apm_v2_m96J01_1775007086632", :frame/id "apm-v2-m96J01-1775007086632", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :workspace/generated-at "2026-04-01T01:31:26.654702Z", :frame/shared-extension-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Local", :frame/module-root "ApmCanaries.Frames.M96J01.Apm_v2_m96J01_1775007086632", :proof/problem-id "m96J01", :workspace/schema "proof-frame-workspace.v1", :frame/workspace-root "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/m96J01/apm-v2-m96J01-1775007086632", :artifacts {:proof-plan "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/m96J01/apm-v2-m96J01-1775007086632/proof-plan.edn", :formal-alignment "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/m96J01/apm-v2-m96J01-1775007086632/formal-alignment.edn", :changelog "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/m96J01/apm-v2-m96J01-1775007086632/changelog.edn", :execute-notes "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/m96J01/apm-v2-m96J01-1775007086632/execute.md", :workspace-readme "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/m96J01/apm-v2-m96J01-1775007086632/README.md", :workspace-metadata "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/m96J01/apm-v2-m96J01-1775007086632/workspace.json", :lean-main "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/M96J01/Apm_v2_m96J01_177500